  <p>When the same risk arrives in every country at once, you get a natural experiment. The 2026 World Cup is exactly that kind of shared shock: a single 39-day window in which sports-betting demand — licensed and illegal — spikes across every market simultaneously. In the run-up to kickoff, a cluster of Asian governments announced enforcement surges against illegal betting, each timed to the tournament. Lined up side by side, the responses reveal less about football than about how each state thinks the fight should be fought.</p>

  <p>Three approaches stand out, and the Philippines sits slightly apart from all of them — not because its tactics differ, but because its legal ground does.</p>

